  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhancing Social Inclusion in Local Governance</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The selection of these issues is borne out of our strive to ensure social justice and social inclusion in the  districts and communities we operate
Social inclusion is integral to the holistic development of any society. To the extent that women and the youth forms majority of the population of the districts, their participation in the decision making processes, programmes and services of their assemblies  is key to development of the districts and the realisation of social justice   
The Fulani community on the other hand, though a minority tribe, have also been totally neglected and experienced some severe forms of social injustice in the districts. They are largely invisible in assemblies&#x2019; plans and interventions. They remained the most underserved groups of people in the districts. There exist virtually no avenues or spaces for them to properly engaged, dialogue and negotiate their rights and demands in the districts and communities they live. Meanwhile, they contribute substanti</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;Capacity Building-Facilitate training of 200 selected members of women, youth and Fulani groups in decentralization planning processes
&#x2022;Facilitate training Gender Equality and Social Inclusiveness (GESI) for district Assembly members and relevant government departments
&#x2022;Social Accountability-networking of groups
&#x2022;Organize community durbars or fora on the decentralization processes</narrative>
  </description>
